  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions has evolved significantly over time. Here's an overview:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Informal money laundering practices existed for centuries\n- Initial focus was primarily on concealing proceeds from illegal activities\n\n2. Key Milestones:\n\n1970 - Bank Secrecy Act (USA)\n- First comprehensive anti-money laundering (AML) legislation\n- Required financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Established reporting and record-keeping requirements\n\n1986 - Money Laundering Control Act (USA)\n- Made money laundering a federal criminal offense\n- Established specific criminal penalties\n\n1989 - Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Establishment\n- International organization developing global AML standards\n- Created comprehensive recommendations for combating financial crimes\n\n1990s-2000s:\n- Expanded international cooperation\n- More sophisticated legal frameworks\n- Increased regulatory requirements for financial institutions\n\n2001 - USA PATRIOT Act\n- Significantly expanded AML regulations\n- Strengthened reporting and monitoring requirements\n- Enhanced international information sharing\n\nThese developments reflect growing global recognition of money laundering as a serious financial crime requiring comprehensive legal strategies.",
